message.content: I am working on building a crm that will allow a payments company to send a merchant a digital application that once approved will be boarded to the payment processor TSYS. the xml docs to connect to TSYS are located in @TSYS-DOCS/ The express docs involve building the account and the PPM files involve building the pricing. Can you review these docs in detail and help craft a plan to start integrating this. Lets put the plan in @docs/

content.text: I'll review the TSYS documentation to understand the Express and PPM integration requirements, then create a comprehensive integration plan.

content.content:
1 2 3 4 5 Introduction to TSYS Express XML 6 7 8 10 11 12 13 14 16 18 20 22 23
15

 17

 19

 21

24

Introduction to TSYS Express XML

25

The TSYS Express XML SDK is designed to provide you with the information necessary to interface with the Express application using XML. The intended audience for the TSYS Express XML SDK is a software developer who is comfortable using XML, SSL, and the other technologies discussed in this help system.

26

The SDK is organized in the following books:

27
  • Introduction to Express XML: This book provides an overview of TSYS Express XML and the TSYS Express XML SDK. The following subjects are covered in the Introduction: 28 29 30 31 32 33
    • TSYS Express XML Overview
    • Connecting to TSYS Express
    • Connectivity
    • Security and Encryption
    • What does TSYS Support?
    • WSDL
    • Commands
    • Message Workflow - Real Time XML
    • Throttle Limits
    • Special Character Handling
    • Responses
    • Client Specific Field Handling
    • Express XML Project Time Lines
    34
  • Digital Certificate: This book provides details on the Digital Certificate Process. The following subjects are covered in Digital Certificate: Digital Certificate Process, CSR Creation, CSR Creation using IKEYMAN, Certificate Request for .NET Clients
  • XML Certification: This book describes the steps that will need to be followed in order for the Client to be become certified to send XML transactions into the production environment.
  • Batch XML: This book provides an overview of Express Batch XML. The book also provides details about the Process and the Processing Windows available for Batch XML.
  • Getting Started: This book provides an overview of the business model and the TE model for merchant and terminal records. Please see Merchants and Terminals for more details.
  • Express XML API: This book provides reference information on the Express XML Application Programmer's Interface.
  • Reporting: This book provides information on obtaining reports related to your Express XML activity.
  • Sample XML Files: This book provides samples files of each XML command available. Real time XML sample files include all commands.

Navigation Tips for the SDK

35

Under the heading Field list you should see some verbiage and words that are fields with links.

36

Next to each link there should be a small box and triangle next to each link:

37

To Navigate through the complete SDK:

38

The up and down triangles shown on the right: are used for Navigation throughout the SDK.

39
  1. By pressing the up arrow the user is navigated up the scrollbar to the previous Chapter/Topic in the list.
  2. Pressing the down arrow, the user is navigated down the scroll bar to the previous Chapter/Topic in the list.

Navigating to the Attributes/Field Definitions:

40

Go to the Field List and links; listed word by word

41
  1. Click on the blue link once to open it.

file.content:
Introduction to TSYS Express XML

The TSYS Express XML SDK is designed to provide you with the information necessary to interface with the Express application using XML. The intended audience for the TSYS Express XML SDK is a software developer who is comfortable using XML, SSL, and the other technologies discussed in this help system.

The SDK is organized in the following books:

  • Introduction to Express XML: This book provides an overview of TSYS Express XML and the TSYS Express XML SDK. The following subjects are covered in the Introduction:
    • TSYS Express XML Overview
    • Connecting to TSYS Express
    • Connectivity
    • Security and Encryption
    • What does TSYS Support?
    • WSDL
    • Commands
    • Message Workflow - Real Time XML
    • Throttle Limits
    • Special Character Handling
    • Responses
    • Client Specific Field Handling
    • Express XML Project Time Lines
  • Digital Certificate: This book provides details on the Digital Certificate Process. The following subjects are covered in Digital Certificate: Digital Certificate Process, CSR Creation, CSR Creation using IKEYMAN, Certificate Request for .NET Clients
  • XML Certification: This book describes the steps that will need to be followed in order for the Client to be become certified to send XML transactions into the production environment.
  • Batch XML: This book provides an overview of Express Batch XML. The book also provides details about the Process and the Processing Windows available for Batch XML.
  • Getting Started: This book provides an overview of the business model and the TE model for merchant and terminal records. Please see Merchants and Terminals for more details.
  • Express XML API: This book provides reference information on the Express XML Application Programmer's Interface.
  • Reporting: This book provides information on obtaining reports related to your Express XML activity.
  • Sample XML Files: This book provides samples files of each XML command available. Real time XML sample files include all commands.

Navigation Tips for the SDK

Under the heading Field list you should see some verbiage and words that are fields with links.

Next to each link there should be a small box and triangle next to each link:

To Navigate through the complete SDK:

The up and down triangles shown on the right: are used for Navigation throughout the SDK.

  1. By pressing the up arrow the user is navigated up the scrollbar to the previous Chapter/Topic in the list.
  2. Pressing the down arrow, the user is navigated down the scroll bar to the previous Chapter/Topic in the list.

Navigating to the Attributes/Field Definitions:

Go to the Field List and links; listed word by word

  1. Click on the blue link once to open it.
  2. By clicking on the field name link, You will see an example of a field name and the full field definition in a table format.

To close the table;

Click on the link a second time to close the link. This should bring the table to its original link format.

To View all Field List tables at once

  1. Scroll down past the list of links.
  2. You should see all the tables listed. Each Field should have its own full field definition in a table format.

1 2 3 4 5 Security and Encryption 6 7 8 9 10 11

Security and Encryption

12

Authorization Requirements

13
  • You must be authorized by the TSYS Express service before a transaction can occur.
  • The client will only be permitted to submit adds, updates, or inquiries for those Banks or BINs for which they possess entitlements.

Products: Adds, Updates, or Inquiries

14

The client will only be permitted to submit adds, updates or inquiries for those products for which they possess entitlements (for example, Credit).

15
  • Data submitted through this service will follow existing TSYS Acquiring Solutions encryption standards.
  • The client will be responsible for ensuring that their preferred connection conforms to current TSYS standards.

Authenticated Process

16

Before a transaction occurs, the client:

17
  • Will be authenticated by the service
  • Will be assigned authentication requirements by TSYS Acquiring Solutions

The service will support connectivity between the client end-point(s) and TSYS Acquiring Solutions using commercially accepted methods (such as Frame Relay, Internet, etc.) over secure protocols (HTTPS).

18

Each client can choose a different connectivity method.

19

Connectivity

20

The client will be allowed to select their preferred connection method from those described.

21
  • Public Internet
  • A TSYS Acquiring Solutions client will connect to TSYS Express via the public internet using a secure protocol.
  • Direct/Leased Line

TSYS Acquiring Solutions Client – TSYS Express with Secure Direct or Leased Line

22

TSYS Client Support

23

The Client will receive support from TSYS Acquiring Solutions to ensure their connection is properly configured to connect to TSYS Express.

Responses

The TSYS Express XML interface provides responses for inquiries and transactions submitted for processing. Similar to a command, a response consists of a response header and a response request.

Related Topics

Commands

Response Header

The response header schema is used for identification purposes and to access audit data. The header contains the following elements:

Element Name

Required

Description

client_id

Yes

Identifies the client making the request

Bank

No

Not used currently. Reserved for future use

Bin

No

Not used currently. Reserved for future use

Response Request

The response request schema performs additional identification, serves client information for the transaction, and returns results (status) and errors. The request contains the following elements:

Element Name

Required

Description

transaction_id

Yes

A unique, numeric, system-generated value.

data

Yes

In response to an AddMerchant command, this returns client-supplied data plus system-supplied default or derived values

In response to an AddNote command, this returns client-supplied data

In response to a MaintainMerchant command, this returns client-supplied data

In response to a View[Entity] or ViewNote command, this returns the requested merchant or terminal data

If an error occurs, this returns client-supplied data

errors

No

A message that identifies the conditions preventing the command from being processed. Depending on the command receiving the error, fields in error and a brief description may be included in this element

status

Yes

A system-generated status code and a message communicating the processing results

Batch Response Structure

Batch job responses will adhere to the following XML schema structure. XML elements are described below.

<jobs-response>
<header>
<batch_id> </batch_id>
<custom_batch_id> </custom_batch_id>
</header>
<job>
<request>
        <command> </command>
        <transaction_id> </transaction_id>
        <custom_record_id> </custom_record_id>
        <custom_user_id> </custom_user_id>
        <data> 
        <!— [CDATA] XML document per the Command Library Schema ->

<error>
<error field=X description=Y/>
</error>
<status>

</status>
</job>
<status>

errors\error

status\error

content.text:
Based on my comprehensive analysis of the TSYS Express XML SDK documentation, I can now provide you with a detailed summary report.

---

# TSYS Express XML SDK - Comprehensive Analysis Report

## 1. Main API Endpoints and Their Purposes

The TSYS Express XML API provides both **Real-Time** and **Batch** processing capabilities with the following primary command categories:

### Merchant Management Commands
- **AddMerchant**: Creates a new merchant record in TSYS Express database
- **AddPPMMerchant**: Creates merchant for clients using both Express and PPM (Portfolio Pricing Manager)
- **MaintainMerchant**: Updates existing merchant information
- **MaintainPPMMerchant**: Updates merchant with PPM integration
- **MaintainMerchantWithoutBETs**: Updates merchant without Billing Element Tables
- **ViewMerchant**: Retrieves merchant information
- **ViewPPMMerchant**: Views merchant with PPM data
- **DeleteMerchantBETs**: Removes both PointToBETs and Merchant BETs

### Merchant Component Commands
- **MaintainMerchantBETs**: Manages merchant billing element tables
- **MaintainMerchantCardPlans**: Manages accepted card types and plans
- **MaintainMerchantChargeRecords**: Manages fee/charge records
- **MaintainMerchantDemographics**: Updates merchant demographic information
- **MaintainMerchantNameAddresses**: Updates merchant contact information
- **MaintainMerchantStatus**: Changes merchant status or association
- **View[Component]**: Various view commands for specific merchant components

### Terminal Management Commands
- **AddTerminal**: Adds payment terminal to TSYS Express
- **MaintainTerminal**: Updates terminal configuration
- **MaintainCardAndHostDetails**: Updates card acceptance and host settings
- **MaintainTerminalDetails**: Updates terminal-specific settings
- **ViewTerminal**: Retrieves terminal information
- **ViewMerchantTerminals**: Lists all terminals for a merchant
- **AddTerminalVendorDeployment**: Configures terminal deployment vendor data
- **ConvertTerminalHierarchy**: Modifies terminal hierarchy structure

### Card Network Registration Commands
- **AddDiscoverRegistration**: Registers merchant with Discover network
- **MaintainDiscoverRegistration**: Updates Discover registration
- **ViewDiscoverRegistration**: Views Discover registration details
- **AddAmexOptBlueReg**: Registers merchant with American Express OptBlue
- **MaintainAmexOptBlueReg**: Updates Amex OptBlue registration
- **DeleteAmexOptBlueReg**: Removes Amex OptBlue registration
- **ViewAmexOptBlueReg**: Views Amex registration details

### Front End Merchant Commands
- **AddFEMerchant**: Adds front-end only merchant (processing only)
- **MaintainFEMerchant**: Updates front-end merchant
- **ViewFEMerchant**: Views front-end merchant data
- **AddFEAmexOptBlueReg**: Registers FE merchant for Amex OptBlue

### Bank-Level Commands  
- **AddBankBET**: Adds bank-level Billing Element Table
- **MaintainBankBET**: Updates bank-level BET
- **ViewBankBET**: Views bank-level BET
- **AddDRT**: Adds Deposit Routing Table (batch only)
- **MaintainDRT**: Updates DRT (batch only)

### Additional Commands
- **AddNote**: Adds notes to merchant or terminal records
- **ViewNotes**: Retrieves notes
- **AddMatchInquiry**: Requests MasterCard MATCH inquiry for merchant
- **ViewMerchantUWStatus**: Views underwriting status
- **ViewMerchantBackupWithholding**: Views backup withholding balances

## 2. Authentication & Connection Requirements

### Security Model
- **Authentication Method**: Client ID and Password (User ID/Password combination)
- **Authorization**: Pre-authorized by TSYS Express service before transactions
- **Entitlements**: Clients can only access Banks/BINs for which they have permissions
- **Product Restrictions**: Limited to products (e.g., Credit) for which they're authorized

### Connectivity Options
1. **Public Internet**: Secure HTTPS connection over public internet
2. **Direct/Leased Line**: Dedicated secure connection to TSYS Express
3. **Frame Relay**: Commercial connection method (legacy)

### Encryption & Protocols
- **Protocol**: HTTPS (secure HTTP)
- **Encryption**: Follows TSYS Acquiring Solutions encryption standards
- **Data Protection**: Client responsible for ensuring connection conforms to TSYS standards
- **Certificate Management**: Requires proper SSL/TLS certificates

### Request Structure
All requests must include:
- **client_id**: Required in header (identifies the client)
- **Bank**: Optional (reserved for future use)
- **BIN**: Optional (reserved for future use)
- **User credentials**: For real-time authentication

## 3. Key Data Structures and XML Schemas

### Request Structure

#### Real-Time Request Format
```xml
<request>
  <header>
    <client_id>CLIENTID</client_id>
    <bank>OPTIONAL</bank>
    <bin>OPTIONAL</bin>
  </header>
  <request>
    <command>CommandName</command>
    <data>
      <![CDATA[
        <!-- Command-specific XML payload -->
      ]]>
    </data>
  </request>
</request>
```

#### Batch Request Format
```xml
<jobs version="">
  <header>
    <custom_batch_id>CLIENT_BATCH_ID</custom_batch_id>
  </header>
  <job>
    <request>
      <command>CommandName</command>
      <custom_record_id>OPTIONAL_RECORD_ID</custom_record_id>
      <custom_user_id>OPTIONAL_USER_ID</custom_user_id>
      <data>
        <![CDATA[ XML document per Command Library Schema -->
      </data>
    </request>
  </job>
  <!-- Multiple <job> elements allowed -->
</jobs>
```

### Response Structure

#### Response Header Elements
- **client_id**: Identifies the client (required)
- **bank**: Reserved for future use
- **bin**: Reserved for future use

#### Response Request Elements
- **transaction_id**: System-generated unique numeric ID (required)
- **data**: Returns submitted data plus system-generated/default values (required)
- **errors**: Field-level error messages with XPath to error location
- **status**: System-generated status code and message (required)

### Core Data Schemas

The documentation references comprehensive schemas for:
- **Merchant Demographics**: Business information, ownership, tax details
- **Name/Address**: Contact information structures
- **Card Plans**: Accepted card types and configurations
- **BETs (Billing Element Tables)**: Fee and pricing structures
- **Charge Records**: Fee/charge definitions
- **Terminal Configuration**: Hardware and processing settings
- **Card Ranges**: Accepted card number ranges

## 4. Workflow for Creating Merchant Accounts

### Standard Merchant Onboarding Flow

```
1. AddMerchant Command
   > Merchant Demographics (required)
   > Name & Address (required)
   > Bank & BIN Assignment (required)
   > Card Plans (optional but recommended)
   > BETs (Billing Element Tables) - pricing
   > Initial Status (typically pending)

2. MaintainMerchantBETs (if not included in AddMerchant)
   > Configure pricing and fees

3. AddTerminal (if merchant needs terminals)
   > Terminal Configuration
   > Card & Host Details
   > Link to Merchant ID

4. Card Network Registration (as needed)
   > AddDiscoverRegistration
   > AddAmexOptBlueReg

5. Verify & Activate
   > ViewMerchant (verify all data)
   > ViewMerchantUWStatus (check underwriting)
   > MaintainMerchantStatus (activate)
```

### PPM-Integrated Merchant Flow

```
1. AddPPMMerchant Command
   > Creates merchant in both Express AND PPM simultaneously
   
2. PPM pricing automatically configured through PPM system

3. AddTerminal (as needed)

4. Card network registration (as needed)

5. Activation through MaintainPPMMerchant
```

### Key Differences
- **AddMerchant**: Standard merchant setup, manual BET configuration
- **AddPPMMerchant**: Integrated with Portfolio Pricing Manager for automated pricing
- **AddFEMerchant**: Front-end only (no backend processing), simplified setup

## 5. Required Fields and Validation Rules

### Minimum Required Fields for AddMerchant

Based on error code S515 ("BadMerchRecord"), minimum fields include:

**Hierarchy Information:**
- Bank Number
- BIN (Bank Identification Number)
- Merchant ID (can be system-generated)

**Business Information:**
- Legal Business Name
- DBA (Doing Business As) Name
- Business Type/Entity Type
- Tax ID (EIN or SSN)

**Contact Information:**
- Physical Business Address
  - Street Address
  - City
  - State/Province
  - Postal Code
  - Country
- Phone Number

**Processing Information:**
- MCC (Merchant Category Code)
- Processing Currency
- Settlement Account Information (DDA)

**Ownership Information:**
- Principal Owner Name
- Owner Ownership Percentage
- Owner Date of Birth
- Owner SSN/Tax ID

### Field-Level Validation

The system validates:
- **Format Validation**: Ensures data matches expected formats (dates, amounts, codes)
- **Business Rules**: Validates against TSYS business logic
- **Cross-Field Validation**: Checks relationships between fields
- **Lookup Validation**: Verifies codes against valid value tables

### Schema Validation
- Must conform to published XSD schemas
- XML must be well-formed
- CDATA sections required for embedded XML payload
- Namespace validation

## 6. Error Handling Patterns

### Status Code Categories

#### Success Codes
- **S000**: Successful Transaction - processed without errors
- **S001**: Processing - transaction currently being processed

#### Informational Codes  
- **S002**: VNumberNotFound - V number doesn't exist (security reasons)
- **S004**: NoRecords - Entity found but no records for inquiry
- **S325**: AmexOptBlue maintenance not supported in MaintainMerchantDemographics

### Technical Error Codes
- **S404**: TechnicalFailure - Failed due to technical dependency
- **S405**: NotAvailable - Record locked by another user, resubmit later
- **S406**: Transaction timed out and rolled back
- **S505**: BadCommand - Invalid/unrecognized command
- **S506**: Command not certified for client
- **S510**: BadSchema - Invalid schema or expired version
- **S520**: BadCSFField - Inactive Client Specific Field

### Validation Error Codes
- **S515**: BadMerchRecord - Minimum required fields missing
- **S999**: BRError - Business rule error (see error element for details)

### Authorization/Authentication Codes
- **S711**: BadClientID - Invalid Client ID
- **S721**: BadPassword - Invalid User ID/Password combination
- **S722**: BadConfig - Invalid implementation options
- **S723**: BlockedMerch - Merchant blocked due to hierarchy block
- **S812**: BadBank - Invalid bank or unauthorized access
- **S822**: BadBIN - Invalid BIN or unauthorized access
- **S823**: Invalid Bank and BIN combination
- **S824**: Invalid BIN and POS combination
- **S825**: BadDiscoverEntity - Not authorized for Discover registration
- **S832**: BadMerch - Invalid merchant or unauthorized access
- **S833**: BadPOSMerchant - Invalid POS Merchant ID
- **S842**: BadTerm - Invalid terminal or unauthorized access

### Batch-Specific Codes
- **S620**: OverThrottle - Transaction limits exceeded for time period
- **S621**: Dup Batch - Duplicate batch filename (identical timestamps)
- **S622**: BatchLimitExceeded - More than 10 files in one window
- **S623**: TranLimitExceeded - More than 5,000 records in one window
- **S624**: MinCritFail - Minimum search criteria not provided
- **S625**: InquiryAddMaintain - Cannot mix inquiry and add/maintain in same batch
- **S626**: Request in progress, try again later (real-time only)
- **S640**: Invalid File Name

### Card Network Codes
- **S701**: No hierarchy provided for Amex
- **S702**: Amex record already exists
- **S703**: Amex record does not exist
- **S704**: Maintenance of Amex ESA not supported
- **S705**: Use MaintainAmexSetup command instead
- **S706**: Amex Delete not allowed for current status
- **S708**: Use MaintainFEAmexOptBlueReg for FE merchants
- **S709**: Use MaintainAmexOptBlueReg command
- **S710**: Bank does not support OptBlue
- **S712**: Merchant type doesn't match data provided
- **S713**: BE MID and BANK not required for FE Merchant
- **S714**: AMEX ESA service retired

### Error Response Structure

Responses include:
- **status\error**: System-level errors with numeric code
- **errors\error**: Field-level errors with XPath to problem field
- **description**: Human-readable error message

### Best Practices for Error Handling

1. **Check Status Code First**: Always examine status code before processing data

```

   > Merchant Demographics (required)

   > Card & Host Details

   > AddDiscoverRegistration
   > AddAmexOptBlueReg

   > ViewMerchantUWStatus (check underwriting)
   > MaintainMerchantStatus (activate)

1. AddPPMMerchant Command
   > Creates merchant in both Express AND PPM simultaneously
   
2. PPM pricing automatically configured through PPM system

3. AddTerminal (as needed)

4. Card network registration (as needed)

5. Activation through MaintainPPMMerchant
```

## 6. Error Handling Patterns

### Status Code Categories

#### Success Codes
- **S000**: Successful Transaction - processed without errors
- **S001**: Processing - transaction currently being processed

#### Informational Codes  
- **S002**: VNumberNotFound - V number doesn't exist (security reasons)
- **S004**: NoRecords - Entity found but no records for inquiry
- **S325**: AmexOptBlue maintenance not supported in MaintainMerchantDemographics

### Technical Error Codes
- **S404**: TechnicalFailure - Failed due to technical dependency
- **S405**: NotAvailable - Record locked by another user, resubmit later
- **S406**: Transaction timed out and rolled back
- **S505**: BadCommand - Invalid/unrecognized command
- **S506**: Command not certified for client
- **S510**: BadSchema - Invalid schema or expired version
- **S520**: BadCSFField - Inactive Client Specific Field

### Validation Error Codes
- **S515**: BadMerchRecord - Minimum required fields missing
- **S999**: BRError - Business rule error (see error element for details)

### Authorization/Authentication Codes
- **S711**: BadClientID - Invalid Client ID
- **S721**: BadPassword - Invalid User ID/Password combination
- **S722**: BadConfig - Invalid implementation options
- **S723**: BlockedMerch - Merchant blocked due to hierarchy block
- **S812**: BadBank - Invalid bank or unauthorized access
- **S822**: BadBIN - Invalid BIN or unauthorized access
- **S823**: Invalid Bank and BIN combination
- **S824**: Invalid BIN and POS combination
- **S825**: BadDiscoverEntity - Not authorized for Discover registration
- **S832**: BadMerch - Invalid merchant or unauthorized access
- **S833**: BadPOSMerchant - Invalid POS Merchant ID
- **S842**: BadTerm - Invalid terminal or unauthorized access

### Batch-Specific Codes
- **S620**: OverThrottle - Transaction limits exceeded for time period
- **S621**: Dup Batch - Duplicate batch filename (identical timestamps)
- **S622**: BatchLimitExceeded - More than 10 files in one window
- **S623**: TranLimitExceeded - More than 5,000 records in one window
- **S624**: MinCritFail - Minimum search criteria not provided
- **S625**: InquiryAddMaintain - Cannot mix inquiry and add/maintain in same batch
- **S626**: Request in progress, try again later (real-time only)
- **S640**: Invalid File Name

### Card Network Codes
- **S701**: No hierarchy provided for Amex
- **S702**: Amex record already exists
- **S703**: Amex record does not exist
- **S704**: Maintenance of Amex ESA not supported
- **S705**: Use MaintainAmexSetup command instead
- **S706**: Amex Delete not allowed for current status
- **S708**: Use MaintainFEAmexOptBlueReg for FE merchants
- **S709**: Use MaintainAmexOptBlueReg command
- **S710**: Bank does not support OptBlue
- **S712**: Merchant type doesn't match data provided
- **S713**: BE MID and BANK not required for FE Merchant
- **S714**: AMEX ESA service retired

Responses include:
- **status\error**: System-level errors with numeric code
- **errors\error**: Field-level errors with XPath to problem field
- **description**: Human-readable error message

   - S404 (TechnicalFailure): Retry with exponential backoff
4. **Log Transaction IDs**: Store for support and troubleshooting
5. **Handle Business Rule Errors (S999)**: Present field-level errors to users
6. **Throttle Management**: Track request counts to avoid S620-S623 errors

- **S710**: Bank does not support OptBlue
- **S712**: Merchant type doesn't match data provided
- **S713**: BE MID and BANK not required for FE Merchant
- **S714**: AMEX ESA service retired

### Error Response Structure

Responses include:
- **status\error**: System-level errors with numeric code
- **errors\error**: Field-level errors with XPath to problem field
- **description**: Human-readable error message

### Best Practices for Error Handling

1. **Check Status Code First**: Always examine status code before processing data
2. **Parse Error Elements**: Extract field-level errors for user feedback
3. **Implement Retry Logic**: 
   - S405 (NotAvailable): Retry after delay
   - S406 (Timeout): Retry with same data
   - S404 (TechnicalFailure): Retry with exponential backoff
4. **Log Transaction IDs**: Store for support and troubleshooting
5. **Handle Business Rule Errors (S999)**: Present field-level errors to users
6. **Throttle Management**: Track request counts to avoid S620-S623 errors

## 7. Sample Code and Examples

### Sample XML File Structure

The documentation references extensive sample files organized by command type:

**Location**: `/TSYS-DOCS/TSYSExpressXMLSDK/SourceFiles/`

**Sample Categories:**
- Merchant samples (AddMerchant, MaintainMerchant, ViewMerchant)
- PPM Merchant samples (AddPPMMerchant)
- Terminal samples (AddTerminal, AddTerminalHostCaptureTAO)
- Amex OptBlue registration samples
- Discover registration samples
- Bank BET samples
- Batch processing samples (AddDRT, BulkFind operations)
- Response file samples

### Batch Processing Limits

- **Maximum Files Per Window**: 10 batch files
- **Maximum Records Per Window**: 5,000 records
- **Batch vs Real-Time**: All real-time commands supported in batch except `ConvertTerminalHierarchy`
- **Inquiry Separation**: Inquiry transactions must be in exclusive batches (cannot mix with Add/Maintain)

### Additional Integration Notes

- **PPM Integration**: Use AddPPMMerchant/MaintainPPMMerchant/ViewPPMMerchant commands exclusively for PPM clients
- **Front-End Merchants**: Use FE-specific commands (AddFEMerchant, MaintainFEMerchant, ViewFEMerchant)
- **Card Network Registration**: Separate commands required for Discover and Amex OptBlue
- **Transaction IDs**: System generates unique transaction_id for tracking
- **Custom IDs**: Clients can provide custom_batch_id, custom_record_id, custom_user_id for their own tracking

---

## Summary

The TSYS Express XML SDK provides a comprehensive merchant boarding and management system with:

- **30+ commands** covering full merchant lifecycle
- **Dual processing modes**: Real-time (HTTPS) and Batch (file-based)
- **Robust security**: Client ID/password authentication with bank/BIN entitlements
- **Flexible merchant types**: Standard, PPM-integrated, and front-end only
- **Card network integration**: Native support for Discover and Amex OptBlue
- **Comprehensive error handling**: 50+ status codes with field-level validation
- **Enterprise features**: Throttling, batch limits, transaction tracking

The key workflow for merchant onboarding is `AddMerchant`  Configure BETs/Pricing  `AddTerminal`  Card Network Registration  Status Activation, with all operations validated against business rules and returning detailed error information for troubleshooting.

Overview

24

TSYS Portfolio Pricing ManagerSM, or PPM, is a pricing tool customers can use to manage pricing and expenses for their merchants. The pricing provided in PPM is integrated with other TSYS systems for statements and billing. Pricing for merchants can be entered and maintained in PPM in two ways, first through a web-based application that allows users to enter and manipulate pricing, and secondly via messages using extensible markup language (XML) which are sent to PPM. A client may add pricing for new merchants or maintain pricing for existing merchants through XML.

25

This guide introduces the concepts and business rules associated with creating and maintaining merchant pricing and expenses via the XML schema that PPM provides. The XML schema is self-documenting. Therefore this guide will not repeat the technical attributes of each tag or message that are described within the schema. Rather, it will focus on how to use the schema to achieve the desired pricing for each merchant, using the business rules that PPM requires to successfully process XML requests. The intended audience for this guide is a technical person or developer who is familiar with XML.

26 27 28 30 31
29

Pricing Profiles

Expense Rate Groups (ERGs)

Relationship Profitability (RP)

Merchant DDA Information

A client may add pricing for new merchants or maintain pricing for existing merchants through XML.

This guide introduces the concepts and business rules associated with creating and maintaining merchant pricing and expenses via the XML schema that PPM provides. The XML schema is self-documenting. Therefore this guide will not repeat the technical attributes of each tag or message that are described within the schema. Rather, it will focus on how to use the schema to achieve the desired pricing for each merchant, using the business rules that PPM requires to successfully process XML requests. The intended audience for this guide is a technical person or developer who is familiar with XML.

PPM Requests

24

The PPM XML provides request functions to retrieve income and expense data from PPM, as well as save, maintain, and delete it. In some cases, the XML will accept request messages that follow the business rules, and will reject request messages that do not. In others, the XML will accept parts of the request message that have proper values and will reject the parts that do not. All requests are subject to the validation rules within PPM.

25

Response files are files PPM transmits back to the sender indicating the success or failure of his request files. They are mirror images of the request files in each case, data included, with additional Outcome tags for each profile, ERG, RP ERG, or Fee Item. Response file samples are included in this section, although more information and samples are included in the subsequent section, PPM Reponses.

26

Requests fall into six general areas, those being merchant pricing, hierarchical pricing, ERGs, RP ERGs, RP Agents, and Merchant DDA data. RP ERGs and RP Agents are available to banks that subscribe to relationship profitability services. While they remain available in the schema, if a bank is not subscribed for these services, any requests sent for them will be rejected.

27

For each general area, requests exist to retrieve data, save and maintain data, and then delete data. Merchant and hierarchy profile requests are usually similar to each other. ERGs and RP ERGs have a different purpose, and therefore do not always follow the same behaviors as profiles. Please examine each request to ensure the request is crafted properly to achieve the desired outcome. Also, when adding or maintaining fee items, please follow the business rules prescribed for each fee category.

28

The following section details these request messages, and some possible responses PPM returns after processing the requests. Additional responses are included in the PPM Responses section.

Profitability

24

This product can manage portfolio profitability through various vehicles to meet the client’s needs. These vehicles include hierarchical pricing profiles, expense rate groups, relationship profitability expense rate groups, and merchant pricing profiles. Together, all of these tools provide a complete profitability picture for the merchant portfolio, including tracking, reporting, statements and billing.

15

24

Pricing Profiles

25

The Merchant Pricing Profile

26

At the heart of this product is the merchant pricing profile. The merchant profile is the set of fees, known as fee items that a merchant has assigned. It can include individual fee items created specifically for that merchant, as well as bank, group or association fee items inherited from a hierarchical pricing profile. The user may also copy another merchant’s pricing, and alter it. The merchant is billed for all items appearing on his pricing profile.

27

In addition to fee items, the merchant pricing profile contains additional information, such as an optional link to an Expense Rate Group and minimum discount information. This is a minimum amount to be charged to a merchant in cases where the merchant may have low activity or low volume. If Relationship Profitability The Relationship Profitability Expense Rate Group (RP ERG) is used, the merchant profile will also include the agent assigned to the merchant.The Hierarchy Pricing Profile

28

Hierarchical pricing profiles are sets of fee items that can be created at different levels of the processor hierarchy, either for a bank, a group or an association, to be inherited by a merchant. Hierarchical profiles are used for pricing that is similar or identical for merchants that fall under that hierarchical entity. Each fee item in a hierarchical profile has a pre-set rate or rates which are applied to each merchant that inherits the profile, without the user having to set up each merchant individually. For example, a merchant belonging to a particular association may inherit an association hierarchical profile, and thus be assigned all of the fee items in that profile automatically. The user then has the ability to override (or cancel out) individual fee items the merchant inherited, to tailor the merchant’s profile to exactly what is needed.

29

If the user wishes to update a particular fee item for all merchants, he may change it in one place, the hierarchical profile, and that change will be effected on each merchant inheriting that profile. Besides inheriting profiles for a merchant, profiles at lower levels of the hierarchy, such as associations, may inherit profiles from higher levels, such as groups and banks. Merchant pricing profiles may inherit from any and all levels of the hierarchy. Merchant pricing profiles themselves may contain up to 80 fee items, and may inherit 80 additional fee items from each level of the hierarchy, if using hierarchical pricing.

Merchant Pricing

At the heart of this product is the merchant pricing profile. The merchant profile is the set of fees, known as fee items that a merchant has assigned. 1 2 3 4 5 XML Batch Messaging 6 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 15 17 19 21 22
14

 16

 18

 20

23

XML Batch Messaging

24

This PPM XML User Guide focuses on the real time use of PPM XML and the content of the individual request messages that can be sent. However, batch files may also be sent to PPM using the BatchRequestMBE.xsd. When a batch file is sent, PPM will send a response file according to the BatchResponseMBE.xsd. Both of these .xsd files contain the same elements as the real time requests that have been listed in previous sections of this document. Both follow the same validations as the real time requests and are subject to the same restrictions and business rules as well. The batch files are categorized into the same basic entities as the real time requests, those being:

25
  • Merchant Pricing Profile
  • Hierarchy Pricing Profile
  • ERG
  • RP ERG
  • RP Agent
  • Merchant DDA

Request messages may be combined in batch requests, if they involve the same basic entities listed above. For example, a merchant pricing batch request may include SaveMerchantPricing, ModifyMerchantFees, DeleteMerchantFees and GetMerchantPricing requests together, but it may not include a SaveHierarchyPricing request or a DeleteErgFees request. Those would be separate batch requests, or included in a different hierarchy pricing batch or ERG batch respectively.

26

When request messages are combined in a batch request, they must follow a logical order. For example, if the client wants a record of a merchant pricing profile before he deletes that profile, he must submit a GetMerchantPricing request before the DeleteMerchantPricing request in the batch file. If he submits the Delete request before the Get request in the batch file, the profile will not exist and the response will contain an error. Similarly, Modify, Delete and Get requests on a merchant or hierarchy profile will return an error if the profile is not found. Thus, when submitting Save, Modify and Get requests all on the same merchant or hierarchy, they must be in that order, that is SaveMerchantPricing, ModifyMerchantFees, and GetMerchantPricing, or an error will be returned.

27

Batch response files behave and may be read in the same manner as the real time response files. They include the response tags that pertain to the real time responses listed in the PPM Responses section of this document.

28

Both the BatchRequestMBE.xsd and the BatchResponseMBE.xsd are part of the PPM XML schema. The following section provides details for sending batch messages to PPM.

29

Mailbox

30

Batch messages must be sent using the Batch RequestMBE.xsd to the client’s mailbox. Each client will have a mailbox that will be set up during client implementation. The system will move the request files to an internal receiving directory. From there they will be processed and corresponding response files will be sent back to the client’s mailbox. The mailbox may be used for other processes for the client, and other services may pull files sent to the mailbox for processing in other systems. Because of this, files sent to the mailbox for PPM batch processing must follow certain naming conventions in order to be routed and processed appropriately.

31

Filenames

32

Each batch request file should follow these naming conventions:

33

ClientShortName_RequestGroupType_BatchID_XXXX.xml

34

The Client Short Name is the client’s name, which will be assigned to the client at client implementation. Using the exact Client Short Name in the filename is required.

35

The Request Group Type is one of the following types of requests. Using this exact wording for the Request Group Type in the filename is required. Request files are denoted by the Req at the end of the Request Group Type. Response files will replace the Req with Res to distinguish them from the request files. All other pieces of the response filename will be identical to the request filename.

36
  • MerchantPricingReq
  • HierarchyPricingReq
  • RpAgentReq
  • ErgReq
  • RpErgReq
  • MerchantDDAReq

The Batch ID is determined by the client. The client may use this ID to distinguish this file (and its corresponding response file) from all other requests. The Batch ID is required. There is no length limitation for the Batch ID. Periods and underscores are not allowed in the Batch ID.

37

The XXXX is any client created text the client wishes to include to further identify the file, and distinguish it from other files. The client created text is not required and may be left blank. There is no length limitation for the client created text. Periods and underscores are not allowed in the client created text.

38

Examples are as follows:

39

FirstLocalBank_MerchantPricingReq_1234567.xml

40

BankOfMine_RpAgentReq_08012013_AddingSWOffice.xml

41

SecondRegionalBank_HierarchyPricingReq_82821_NewAssociation.xml

42

Schedule

43

Request files will be picked up and processed several times a day. The exact schedule is to be determined. A response file will be returned in the client’s mailbox after each request file is processed.

44

Limits

45

There are no limits as to file size for a request file. There is no limit to the number of transactions that may be included in each request file. There is no limit to the number of batch request files a client can send per day.

46

Response Files

47

Once the request file is processed PPM will send a response file back to the client’s mailbox. The response file will follow the naming conventions of the request file, with a Res replacing the Req in the filename, as noted above. One response file will be sent back for each request file.

1 2 3 4 5 Expense Rate Groups (ERGs) 6 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 15 17 19 21 22
14

 16

 18

 20

23

Expense Rate Groups (ERGs)

24

Expenses that a client incurs can be tracked in the system. These may be tracked for reporting purposes, or may be sent to a different client system that needs this data. They may also be used to pass along fees to the merchant in fee items on the merchant’s pricing profile. Like pricing fee items, they may be organized into pre-defined sets as well, called expense rate groups, or ERGs. ERGs can be created and used at any level of the hierarchy: bank, group or association. They may also be created for the client overall, where all banks under the client may use it. They may be attached to a merchant profile, in order to track expenses for a given merchant, or included in profit and loss reporting. Many merchants may be associated with a particular ERG, so the client need only update these expenses in one place to achieve an update to all merchants associated with that ERG. ERGs may have up to 100 fee items each.

Expense Rate Groups (ERGs)

Expenses that a client incurs can be tracked in the system. These may be tracked for reporting purposes, or may be sent to a different client system that needs this data. They may also be used to pass along fees to the merchant in fee items on the merchant’s pricing profile. Like pricing fee items, they may be organized into pre-defined sets as well, called expense rate groups, or ERGs. ERGs can be created and used at any level of the hierarchy: bank, group or association. They may also be created for the client overall, where all banks under the client may use it. They may be attached to a merchant profile, in order to track expenses for a given merchant, or included in profit and loss reporting. 1 2 3 4 5 Relationship Profitability (RP) 6 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 15 17 19 21 22
14

 16

 18

 20

23

Relationship Profitability (RP)

24

The Relationship Profitability Expense Rate Group (RP ERG)

25

The Relationship Profitability Expense Rate Group is a type of Expense Rate Group, or ERG, that defines expense rates for individual agents or ISOs. The fee items included in an RP ERG differ from fee items in an ERG in that RP ERG fee items are fees that the agent pays to another agent that is higher up in the agent hierarchy, if the client’s agent structure uses a hierarchy. Many merchants can be assigned to an agent. Agents will pay out fees, and agents higher in the chain will receive this income according to the agent hierarchical structure that the client creates. RP ERGs function in the same way as ERGs, with one additional rate method for revenue sharing. RP ERGs may follow a bank hierarchy or an agent hierarchy.

26

RP ERGs differ from ERGs in that the expenses serve different purposes. Each merchant profile may be associated to one ERG and also one agent. Each agent is assigned to either a flat percentage rate or to an RP ERG for revenue sharing. Many agents under the same bank may be associated to the same RP ERG, if their payout structures are the same. RP ERGs may have up to 100 fee items each.

27

Note: Relationship Profitability is an optional service. If a bank does not subscribe to this service, RP requests will be rejected if sent. If not subscribing to Relationship Profitability, please ignore the RP ERG and RP Agent sections of the PPM schema.

28

The Relationship Profitability (RP) Agent Profile

29

This product provides the ability to manage agent expenses and payouts with the relationship profitability functionality. Agents may be assigned to other agents above them, in an agent hierarchy structure, with up to ten levels of hierarchy. Higher level agents may also both maintain and assign RP ERGs to agents below them in the hierarchy.

30

Notes: Assigning an agent to an RP ERG is optional. If he has an RP ERG associated with his agent profile, that RP ERG will determine his fee structure. If he is not associated with an RP ERG, the agent must have an overall income rate entered that will apply for all activity credited to him. He must have only one of these options, not both.

Fee Category Business Rules

24

Some fee item attributes, or tags associated with each fee, are required for all fee items. Others are conditionally required, and still others, depending on the fee category, will result in an error. The rules of each fee category determine which settings and rates are applicable for a given fee item. These rules are enforced in the PPM GUI, but are not explained in the PPM XML schema. The business rules section explains these rules by fee category, so that XML requests are accepted with minimal errors.

25

If a field is not present in the table for a given fee category then it does not apply to that category. Only the fields that apply to each category are listed. Entering a value for a field that is not listed for a particular category will result in a validation error when processing that fee item, and the fee item will be rejected.

content.content:
1 2 3 4 5 Fee Items 6 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 15 17 19 21 22
14

 16

 18

 20

23

Fee Items

24

A fee item is a fee or collection of fees (represented as one fee item) that can be bundled up together and billed as one fee to the merchant. Fee item refers to each fee and its associated attributes. It is the building block of pricing profiles and expense groups alike. Each fee item has defining characteristics which describe the way it will be processed for a merchant. One of these is the Fee Category. Fee Categories group fee items that behave in a similar manner. They also drive reporting. Each fee category has different options, settings and specific business rules associated with it. Which fee category is selected, along with the rate method and fee structure, determines how a fee will behave.

25

Each fee item may have one or more rate methods associated with it. These methods determine how the fee item is calculated and applied. A fee item may have a rate based on percentage, or per item, or overall volume. Tiered pricing and pass-through pricing are also available in some cases. Rate methods are applicable to income fee items and expense items alike.

26

Fee items have a fee structure, also known as a key structure. These terms are interchangeable, with fee structure being used in the GUI, and key structure being used in the XML schema. The key structure is a list of one to four values in addition to the fee category that help define the type of activity to which the fee is applied. Before a fee item can be used, it must have a valid key structure associated with it. Merchant profiles, hierarchy profiles, ERGs and RP ERGs may each have up to 4000 key structures associated with them. The list of valid key structures is updated periodically. Because of this, a complete and current list of available key structures and valid combinations is available outside of this document.

27

The PPM Key Structure File provides a comprehensive list of values that are currently available in PPM. The file enables you to:

28
  • Identify which values are available by Fee Category at the various key levels, and how they relate to values at other key levels.
  • Retrieve new values when new types of fees or activity are introduced in PPM, for example, during a compliance release or to support a new product and its associated billing items.
  • Interpret fee structure values provided in the PPM Profitability and Residual File.
  • Identify values that are needed for PPM XML.

1 2 3 4 5 Get Merchant Pricing 6 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 14 16 18 20 22 23
15

 17

 19

 21

24

Get Merchant Pricing

25

The GetMerchantPricing request returns both merchant and hierarchical pricing profile and fee information for an existing merchant. (Profile information includes the ID of any associated ERG and minimum discount information.) It does not write anything to PPM or update the merchant’s information in any way. If PPM finds a match for the merchant in the system but cannot find a profile for that merchant, PPM returns the merchant information and any fee items inherited from any hierarchical profiles associated with the merchant. If PPM cannot find a match for the merchant at all, it returns an error and rejects the file. If there are no fee items attached to the merchant PPM returns only the profile. If there are fee items attached to the merchant, PPM returns the profile and all fee items. PPM returns all active fee items, including current and future fee items, and expired fee items from the current month. It will not return expired fee items from previous months. There is no separate operation for retrieving only the merchant’s fee items – they always accompany the profile in this operation.

26

GetMerchantPricing can be used to check existing profile or fee information before determining the actions needed, if any, on a specified merchant. The data that is returned can also be sent on to other systems used by the client.

27

While fee items sent into PPM via XML will always be saved as complete, fee items returned by GetMerchantPricing may be in either Complete or Work in Progress status. This status is indicated by the FeeStatus tag included in the response file. The GetMerchantPricing request also pulls any hierarchical fee items applied to the merchant profile, as well as fee items directly on the merchant’s profile. It will not include expenses from an ERG that is associated with a merchant’s profile.

28

Status Each response file has a Status tag at the beginning of the response file to indicate the overall outcome of the request. The tag includes a Code and Description of the status. After the Status the response file continues with a copy of the data that was sent in the original request., Profile Status The Profile Status is included after the profile request and before the fees, if fees are sent with the request. The ERG Status is included after the ERG request and before the fees, if fees are sent with the request., and ERG Status The Profile Status is included after the profile request and before the fees, if fees are sent with the request. The ERG Status is included after the ERG request and before the fees, if fees are sent with the request. relate to the request file or merchant as a whole. Within each fee the response file provides several tags regarding status and outcome of the processing of that fee item. These are found underneath the fee at the end of the Fees tag. The FeeStatus tag indicates whether the fee is in Work In Progress (WIP) status or is Complete. For Save, Add, and Modify requests containing fees, if a fee is successfully updated or added, the FeeStatus will always come back as Complete, since the request itself updates the fee to a Complete status. If the fee is not successfully updated or added, this tag will not be present in the response. For Get Requests, this tag will return the fee status, either Work In Progress or Complete. For clients only using the XML, this status will always be Complete, but for clients who use both the GUI and XML, the Status may be either Complete or Work In Progress. These apply to all fees, whether on profiles, ERGs or RP ERGs.

29

A sample of the FeeStatus tag is as follows.

30

31

Scenario

32

A customer service representative at the client may process a call from a merchant or the merchant’s acquirer, and need to see the latest pricing information for the merchant. The customer service representative may pull up the merchant in the client’s internal customer service software to view the pricing. To do this, a GetMerchantPricing request may be sent to PPM, and the merchant data sent back in the response file may be used to populate the customer service software, so the rep can complete his call.

33

Process Flow

Response

41

PPM sends back the merchant profile, with success message, and all fee items associated with this merchant. The sample below shows the merchant profile, response information, and the first fee on the profile.

1# MPA to Express & PPM Integration Plan
     2
     3## Overview
     4
     5This document outlines the implementation plan for automating the conversion of Merchant Processing Applications (MPAs) into Express account creation followed by Portfolio Pricing Manager (PPM) pricing setup within the TSYS ecosystem.
     6
     7## Business Flow
     8
     9```
    10MPA Application  Express Account Creation  PPM Pricing Configuration  Account Activation
    11```
    12
    13## MPA Data Structure Analysis
    14
    15Based on the CardConnect MPA document, the following key data sections are available:
    16
    17### Business Information
    18- **Business Legal Name** - Primary merchant identifier
    19- **DBA Name** - Doing Business As name
    20- **Tax ID (EIN)** - Federal tax identification
    21- **Tax Filing Method** - EIN vs SSN
    22- **Type of Ownership** - Corporation, LLC, Partnership, etc.
    23- **Industry (MCC)** - Merchant Category Code
    24- **Business Description**
    25- **Business Start Date**
    26- **Website**
    27- **Business Phone**
    28
    29### Address Information
    30- **Business Address** - Physical location
    31- **Business Legal Mailing Address** - Registered address
    32- **Ship To Address** - Equipment shipping
    33
    34### Owner Information
    35- **Business Owner(s)** - Up to 4 additional owners
    36  - Name, Title, SSN, Date of Birth
    37  - Ownership percentage
    38  - Personal guarantee status
    39  - Contact information and address
    40
    41### Banking Details
    42- **Deposit Bank Account** - Primary funding account
    43- **Withdrawal Bank Account** - Optional separate account
    44- **Account Type** - Checking/Savings
    45- **Routing/Account Numbers**
    46
    47### Processing Information
    48- **Processing Volume**
    49  - Average Monthly Card Volume
    50  - Average Transaction Amount
    51- **Transaction Modes**
    52  - In Person percentage
    53  - Telephone percentage
    54  - Online percentage
    55- **Product/Service Delivery** - Delivery timeframes
    56
    57### Pricing Structure
    58- **Discount Fees** - Credit/Debit card rates
    59- **Transaction Fees** - Per-transaction charges
    60- **Monthly Fees** - Recurring charges
    61- **Equipment Fees** - Terminal costs
    62
    63## Express Account Creation Mapping
    64

# MPA to Express & PPM Integration Plan

## Overview

This document outlines the implementation plan for automating the conversion of Merchant Processing Applications (MPAs) into Express account creation followed by Portfolio Pricing Manager (PPM) pricing setup within the TSYS ecosystem.

## Business Flow

```
MPA Application  Express Account Creation  PPM Pricing Configuration  Account Activation
```

## MPA Data Structure Analysis

Based on the CardConnect MPA document, the following key data sections are available:

### Business Information
- **Business Legal Name** - Primary merchant identifier
- **DBA Name** - Doing Business As name
- **Tax ID (EIN)** - Federal tax identification
- **Tax Filing Method** - EIN vs SSN
- **Type of Ownership** - Corporation, LLC, Partnership, etc.
- **Industry (MCC)** - Merchant Category Code
- **Business Description**
- **Business Start Date**
- **Website**
- **Business Phone**

### Address Information
- **Business Address** - Physical location
- **Business Legal Mailing Address** - Registered address
- **Ship To Address** - Equipment shipping

### Owner Information
- **Business Owner(s)** - Up to 4 additional owners
  - Name, Title, SSN, Date of Birth
  - Ownership percentage
  - Personal guarantee status
  - Contact information and address

### Banking Details
- **Deposit Bank Account** - Primary funding account
- **Withdrawal Bank Account** - Optional separate account
- **Account Type** - Checking/Savings
- **Routing/Account Numbers**

### Processing Information
- **Processing Volume**
  - Average Monthly Card Volume
  - Average Transaction Amount
- **Transaction Modes**
  - In Person percentage
  - Telephone percentage
  - Online percentage
- **Product/Service Delivery** - Delivery timeframes

### Pricing Structure
- **Discount Fees** - Credit/Debit card rates
- **Transaction Fees** - Per-transaction charges
- **Monthly Fees** - Recurring charges
- **Equipment Fees** - Terminal costs

## Express Account Creation Mapping

### Required Express Fields from MPA

| Express Field | MPA Source | Notes |
|---------------|------------|--------|
| Merchant Name | Business Legal Name | Primary identifier |
| DBA | DBA Name | Display name |
| Federal Tax ID | Tax ID (EIN) | Business identifier |
| MCC | Industry (MCC) | Merchant category |
| Business Type | Type of Ownership | Legal structure |
| Address | Business Address | Physical location |
| Mailing Address | Business Legal Mailing Address | Correspondence |
| Phone | Business Phone | Contact |
| Website | Website | Online presence |
| Principal Info | Business Owner Information | Key stakeholder data |
| Bank Account | Deposit Bank Account | Settlement account |

### Express API Endpoints (Based on TSYS SDK Structure)

```xml
<!-- Merchant Creation Request -->
<MerchantRequest>
  <BusinessInfo>
    <LegalName>{Business Legal Name}</LegalName>
    <DBAName>{DBA Name}</DBAName>
    <TaxID>{Tax ID}</TaxID>
    <MCC>{Industry MCC}</MCC>
    <BusinessType>{Type of Ownership}</BusinessType>
  </BusinessInfo>
  <ContactInfo>
    <Phone>{Business Phone}</Phone>
    <Website>{Website}</Website>
  </ContactInfo>
  <Address>
    <Physical>{Business Address}</Physical>
    <Mailing>{Business Legal Mailing Address}</Mailing>
  </Address>
  <BankAccount>
    <RoutingNumber>{Routing Number}</RoutingNumber>
    <AccountNumber>{Account Number}</AccountNumber>
    <AccountType>{Account Type}</AccountType>
  </BankAccount>
</MerchantRequest>
```

## PPM Pricing Configuration

### PPM Schema Integration

Based on the available XSD schemas, PPM supports:

- **MerchantPricing.xsd** - Core pricing structure
- **ProfilePricing.xsd** - Pricing profiles and templates
- **FeeItemMaster.xsd** - Fee definitions
- **MerchantDDA.xsd** - Bank account management
- **ERG.xsd** - Entity Relationship Groups

### Pricing Data Mapping

| PPM Element | MPA Source | Schema Reference |
|-------------|------------|------------------|
| Discount Fees | Visa/MC/Discover/Amex Credit Card Discount Fee | MerchantPricingRequestType |
| Transaction Fees | Debit Card Transaction Fee | FeesRequestType |
| Monthly Fees | Various monthly fees | FeesRequestType |
| Bank Account | Deposit Bank Account | MerchantDDAType |
| Merchant Info | Business details | MerchantType |

### PPM API Structure

```xml
<!-- PPM Pricing Request -->
<MerchantPricingRequest>
  <Merchant>
    <BankNum>{Bank Number}</BankNum>
    <MerchantNum>{Merchant Number from Express}</MerchantNum>
  </Merchant>
  <Fees>
    <DiscountFees>
      <VisaCredit>{Visa Credit Card Discount Fee}</VisaCredit>
      <MastercardCredit>{Mastercard Credit Card Discount Fee}</MastercardCredit>
      <DiscoverCredit>{Discover Credit Card Discount Fee}</DiscoverCredit>
      <AmexCredit>{Amex Credit Card Discount Fee}</AmexCredit>
    </DiscountFees>
    <TransactionFees>
      <DebitFee>{Debit Card Transaction Fee}</DebitFee>
    </TransactionFees>
  </Fees>
</MerchantPricingRequest>
```

## Implementation Workflow

### Phase 1: MPA Data Extraction
1. **Parse MPA PDF/Form**
   - Extract structured data from MPA document
   - Validate required fields
   - Handle multiple owner scenarios
   - Process banking information

2. **Data Transformation**
   - Convert MPA fields to Express format
   - Map pricing structure to PPM schema
   - Handle data type conversions
   - Apply business rule validations

### Phase 2: Express Account Creation
1. **Pre-validation**
   - Verify business information
   - Check for duplicate merchants
   - Validate banking details
   - Confirm regulatory requirements

2. **Account Creation**
   - Submit Express merchant creation request
   - Handle response and capture merchant ID
   - Process any error conditions
   - Store Express account details

### Phase 3: PPM Pricing Setup
1. **Pricing Configuration**
   - Map MPA pricing to PPM structure
   - Create merchant pricing profile
   - Configure fee schedules
   - Set up DDA accounts

2. **Profile Activation**
   - Apply pricing templates
   - Activate merchant profile
   - Validate pricing setup
   - Generate confirmation

### Phase 4: Validation & Monitoring
1. **End-to-End Testing**
   - Verify account creation
   - Confirm pricing accuracy
   - Test transaction processing
   - Validate settlement

24

Save Merchant Pricing

25

The SaveMerchantPricing request saves a new profile, or completely overwrites an existing profile for a merchant. The merchant must exist in TSYS’ boarding system before SaveMerchantPricing can be sent, or the request will be rejected. If fee items are sent in the request, PPM will ensure the number of fee items and key structures in the request do not exceed the limit for merchant profiles. PPM will validate the profile, and upon passing validation, add the profile (or overwrite it if it already exists in PPM) as complete.

26

Then PPM will validate any fee items sent in the request. If no fee items are sent, the existing fee items in PPM (if any) will remain on the merchant’s profile. Likewise, if no fee items pass validation, PPM will reject them all, and the existing fee items in PPM (if any) will remain on the merchant’s profile. If some or all of the fee items in the request file pass validation, PPM will remove all existing fee items on the merchant’s profile and replace them with the fee items from the request file that passed validation. PPM will reject the fee items that do not pass validation.

27

Included in the profile is minimum discount information. This applies to the merchant as a whole and not to any one fee. There is only one amount to be entered, rather than a variety of rate methods, and a rate restriction is available that can be set on the amount. (An option is present in the schema to also restrict a percent rate. This option should not be used.)

28

All fee items will be saved as complete, and will be subjected to the full set of validations before being saved to the profile. Fee items sent in via XML may not be saved as ‘work in progress’ fee items. Use SaveMerchantPricing to completely refresh or insert a merchant profile and all of its fee items. Use AddMerchantFees to add fee items without deleting existing fee items. Use ModifyMerchantFees to update specific existing fee items without affecting others.

29

Note: The merchant must exist in TSYS’ boarding system before SaveMerchantPricing can be sent, or the request will be rejected. The merchants themselves are set up in the billing system outside of PPM; there is no XML request message to create a merchant. The XML commands provided here create, maintain and delete pricing profiles associated with the merchant, after the merchant has been created in the system.

30

Scenario

31

A client may have boarded a new merchant and must set up his pricing. To do this, a SaveMerchantPricing request may be sent to PPM, which includes a profile for the merchant and all appropriate fee items. PPM will validate and add all information that is sent, completing the merchant’s pricing profile.

32

Another possible scenario is if a client wants to completely rework a merchant’s pricing, perhaps due to a contract negotiation or other occurrence. In this scenario PPM will remove the old profile and fee items, and upon successful validation of the items in the request file, add back the new profile and fee items for the merchant. This scenario is possible but may be rare. More likely a merchant’s pricing may be renegotiated in one particular area, for example interchange fees. In that case the AddMerchantFees, ModifyMerchantFees, and DeleteMerchantFees would be used to revamp only the fee items in the interchange category.

33

If a merchant is pointed to a certain ERG, the client may want to change that merchant’s ERG, or phase out the ERG altogether. Before the client can successfully delete an ERG, he must make sure no merchants are pointing to it. In both of these scenarios, he may use SaveMerchantPricing to overlay the merchant’s profile, including a new ERG assignment. (He may then go on to delete the ERG using the DeleteErg request, if applicable.)

34

Process Flow

Volume Tiered Rates

Here is a fee item with volume tiered pricing. (Only the pricing tag of the fee is displayed.) The MaxFactor, though a tag in tiered pricing, is not needed and will be ignored if sent. The MaxFactor is calculated from the MinFactor of the next tier. The MaxFactor of the first tier in the example below will be calculated as 49,999. The MaxFactor of the second tier in the example is calculated as 999,999 (the high limit on tiered fees).

60

This fee item is effective from May 31, 2013 through the following May. It uses Pick-a-Tier Volume tiered pricing, based on Number. The first tier, for the first 49,999 transactions applies $.125 per transaction. The second tier, for any additional transactions, applies $.12 per transaction.

61

62

Pass Through Interchange Rates

63

Here is an example of a Pass-Through Interchange fee that is effective May, 2014 and is charged monthly on an ongoing basis.

64

Interchange Differential Rates

66

Here is an example of an Interchange Differential pricing fee item that is effective May, 2014 and is charged monthly on an ongoing basis. It compares the actual interchange rate for each transaction to the qualified rates entered, here a Per Item (Amount) of 0.16 and a percentage of 1.62. Only gross sales (not credits) are used in the calculation (as indicated by the CountChargeType The Count Net/Gross/Both Indicator specifies how to apply the per item pricing, based on the sales and credits activity. The Count indicator tells the system how to treat the number of items. If the indicator is set to Gross, only sales are applied. If it is set to Net, sales – (minus) credits are applied. If it is set to Both, sales + (plus) credits are applied. and AmountChargeType The Amount Net/Gross/Both Indicator specifies how to apply the percentage pricing, based on the sales and credits activity. The Amount indicator tells the system how to treat the dollar amount of items. If the indicator is set to Gross, only sales are applied. If it is set to Net, sales – (minus) credits are applied. If it is set to Both, sales + (plus) credits are applied. tags).

67

68

Effective Rates

69

Here is an example of Effective Rates stacked within a fee item. Most fee items do not require a Stop Date The Stop Date is the date after which a fee item expires. This date may be used to mark the end of the application of this fee item, or to stop the current rate and begin the next rate, if using the effective rate features in the Date Rate tag (located within the Pricing tag).. However, when sending multiple effective rates, the Stop Date is required on all but the final effective rate. (A Stop Date may be sent on the final effective rate, but it is not required.

70

71

Miscellaneous Fixed Fee

72

Here is a fee item in the Miscellaneous Fixed Fee Category (for equipment). The fee is a one-time fee that is applied for the month of May, 2014, and charges the merchant for the purchase of three terminals (Count) at $30.00 (total of $90.00). Sales tax is applied to the purchase. For this fee (as a one-time fee) to be applied to the merchant, the StopDate must be on the last calendar day or last processing day of the month.

73

For Miscellaneous Fixed fees, a Count may be entered along with the fixed rate. This field acts as a multiplier, causing the fixed rate in the Per Item ($) amount field to act as a true per item rate.

74

Note: The Count field can accept a numeric value (1-999999) or can be left blank. However, if a zero (0) is entered, the calculation will be performed as if it is a one (1).

75

For example, a merchant may rent three terminals at $30 per month each, for a total of $90. The client may combine these terminals in one fee item, using the Count value to indicate how many terminals are rented. The Per Item ($) amount ($30) indicates the cost per terminal, providing a detailed display on the statement. The system will then calculate a total of $90.

76

Note: For complete reporting to the merchant, also select Display on Statement: Count Display on Statement: Count provides an option to display on the merchant statement the total number of items used to calculate the fee. For example, using this setting would display how many authorization transactions a merchant had for a particular auth fee. and Display Rate on Statement Display Rates on Statement provides an option to display the rates for a particular fee item on the merchant’s statement. It will display Per Item ($) and Percent rates for Per Item, Percent, Pass Through and Tiered pricing. Rates applied over and above the Pass Through Rates will be combined into the Percent and Per Item ($) rates displayed..

77

78

Here is an example of a Discount fee.

These elements are for the profile only, and do not include fees. For fees please see fee request messages.

# TSYS Portfolio Pricing Manager (PPM) XML SDK - Comprehensive Analysis Report

## Executive Summary

TSYS Portfolio Pricing Manager (PPM) is a pricing and billing management system that enables clients to configure merchant pricing, track expenses, and manage fee structures for their merchant portfolios. The system integrates with TSYS Express (merchant account creation) and operates through both a web-based GUI and XML API interfaces.

**Critical Integration Flow:**
```
Express Account Creation  PPM Pricing Configuration  Statement/Billing Integration
```

The merchant must exist in TSYS's boarding system (via Express) **before** PPM pricing can be configured.

## 1. Main API Operations: Batch vs Real-Time

### Real-Time Operations (WSDL-based)

**Location:** `/Users/coreyyoung/Desktop/Projects/tsyscrm/TSYS-DOCS/PPM-XML-WSDLSchemas-RealTime/MerchantPricingService.wsdl`

PPM provides a comprehensive SOAP-based web service with the following operation categories:

#### Merchant Pricing Operations
- **SaveMerchantPricing** - Creates new or overwrites existing merchant pricing profile
- **GetMerchantPricing** - Retrieves merchant pricing profile and all associated fees
- **DeleteMerchantPricing** - Removes merchant pricing profile entirely
- **AddMerchantFees** - Adds new fees to existing profile without affecting others
- **ModifyMerchantFees** - Updates specific existing fees
- **AddOrModifyMerchantFees** - Combined operation for adding or modifying fees
- **DeleteMerchantFees** - Removes specific fees from profile
- **ModifyMerchantFeesFrequencyAndRates** - Updates only frequency and rate information
- **ApplyTemplatesToMerchant** - Applies pre-configured pricing templates
- **ReassignTemplateToMerchant** - Changes template assignment

#### Hierarchy Pricing Operations
- **SaveHierarchyPricing** - Creates/updates pricing at bank, group, or association level
- **GetHierarchyPricing** - Retrieves hierarchical pricing structures
- **DeleteHierarchyPricing** - Removes hierarchical pricing
- **AddHierarchyFees** - Adds fees to hierarchy level
- **ModifyHierarchyFees** - Updates hierarchy fees

#### ERG (Expense Rate Group) Operations
- **AddErg** - Creates new expense rate group
- **ModifyErg** - Updates ERG configuration
- **DeleteErg** - Removes ERG
- **GetErg** - Retrieves ERG details
- **AddErgFees** - Adds expense fees to ERG
- **ModifyErgFees** - Updates ERG fees
- **DeleteErgFees** - Removes ERG fees

#### RP (Relationship Profitability) Operations
- **AddRpErg** - Creates RP expense rate group for agent commissions
- **ModifyRpErg** - Updates RP ERG
- **DeleteRpErg** - Removes RP ERG
- **GetRpErg** - Retrieves RP ERG details
- **AddRpErgFees** - Adds RP fees
- **ModifyRpErgFees** - Updates RP fees
- **DeleteRpErgFees** - Removes RP fees
- **AddRpAgent** - Creates agent profile
- **ModifyRpAgent** - Updates agent
- **DeleteRpAgent** - Removes agent
- **GetRpAgent** - Retrieves agent details

#### DDA (Direct Deposit Account) Operations
- **SaveMerchantDDA** - Configures merchant bank account information
- **GetMerchantDDA** - Retrieves DDA details
- **DeleteMerchantDDA** - Removes DDA configuration

#### Fee Item Master Operations (2023+ Features)
- **GetFeeItemMaster** - Retrieves fee item master data
- **GetFeeItemMasterFeeDetails** - Detailed fee item information
- **AddFeeItemMasterFees** - Adds fees to master catalog
- **ModifyFeeItemMasterFees** - Updates fee items in catalog
- **ModifyFeeItemMasterFeesMinimal** - Limited update operation

#### Income Rate Group Operations (2023+)
- **AssignIrgsToMerchant** - Assigns Income Rate Groups to merchant
- **UnAssignIrgsFromMerchant** - Removes IRG assignments

### Batch Operations (File-based)

**Schemas:** 
- `/Users/coreyyoung/Desktop/Projects/tsyscrm/TSYS-DOCS/PPM-XML-Schemas-Batch/BatchRequestMBE.xsd`
- `/Users/coreyyoung/Desktop/Projects/tsyscrm/TSYS-DOCS/PPM-XML-Schemas-Batch/BatchResponseMBE.xsd`

#### Batch Processing Characteristics

**Delivery Method:**
- Files uploaded to client-specific mailbox
- Processed multiple times per day (schedule TBD during implementation)
- Response files returned to same mailbox

**File Naming Convention:**
```
ClientShortName_RequestGroupType_BatchID_XXXX.xml
```

**Request Group Types:**
- `MerchantPricingReq` / `MerchantPricingRes`
- `HierarchyPricingReq` / `HierarchyPricingRes`
- `ErgReq` / `ErgRes`
- `RpErgReq` / `RpErgRes`
- `RpAgentReq` / `RpAgentRes`
- `MerchantDDAReq` / `MerchantDDARes`

**Batch Rules:**
- Requests of the same entity type can be combined (e.g., SaveMerchantPricing + ModifyMerchantFees)
- Cannot mix entity types (e.g., merchant pricing + hierarchy pricing in same file)
- Must maintain logical order (Get before Delete, Save before Modify)
- No file size or transaction limits
- Unlimited daily batch submissions

**Example Filenames:**
```
FirstLocalBank_MerchantPricingReq_1234567.xml
BankOfMine_RpAgentReq_08012013_AddingSWOffice.xml
SecondRegionalBank_HierarchyPricingReq_82821_NewAssociation.xml
```
